B. Finite Mixture Model
As shown in Fig. 1, there obviously exist several homogeneous clusters in the data. To characterize in what scope a certain classifier distinguishes data, Yeung et al. [24] introduced the definition of homospace as follows. Definition 1: Suppose a training set T can be divided into I partitions, i.e., H1, . . . , HI , where H1 ‚à™ ¬∑ ¬∑ ¬∑ ‚à™ HI = T and Hi ‚à© H j = ‚àÖ, i, j = 1, . . . , I and i = j . If data points in each partition Hi are considered by the classifier C to share the same distribution trend, which can empirically be measured by the covariance matrix, these partitions, i.e., H1, . . . , HI , are called homospaces of the classifier C for the training set T . As mentioned in Definition 1, each partition Hi shares the same distribution trend. It means that the distribution of the whole data consists of several subdistributions. Thus, the distribution for each class can be presented by a finite mixture model as follows:
p(x) =
