D. Kernelization
As mentioned in (6), Algorithm 1 only considers the linearly separable case of SMPM. To handle the linearly nonseparable case, this section describes the kernelization of SMPM. In particular, we map n-dimensional data points into a highdimensional reproducing kernel Hilbert space (RKHS) R f [28] by a mapping function œÜ : Rn ‚Üí R f . Thus, the SMPM finds a linear classifier in the RKHS R f . The corresponding linear classifier in RKHS is represented as aT œÜ(z) = b, where a, œÜ(z) ‚àà R f , and b ‚àà R, which would handle the linearly nonseparable case in the original space Rn. Note that the linear classifier in the RKHS corresponds to a nonlinear hyperplane in the original space. Assume that the training data points of the kth homospace
